# Arch Linux Documentation - OS_Wiki

System Name: Arch Linux
Kernel: Linux (rolling release, latest kernel)
Based on: Nothing (independent)
Created by: Judd Vinet (initially for the i686 architecture)
Maintained by: Arch Linux Community
Initial release: 2002
Source model: Open source
License: GPL / 0BSD
Architecture support: x86_64 (amd64) official support; unofficial ARM and i686 (32-bit) support
Package manager: Pacman (binary), created by Judd Vinet
Desktop Environment: Any (CLI installation)
System type: Desktop
Target audience: Advanced users, power users, rolling-release enthusiasts, and technology students.
Not recommended for: Beginners, people coming from Windows with no computer experience, and those who want a ready-made, plug-and-play system.
Official site: https://archlinux.org/
ISO size for download: ~1.4 GB (latest version)
Minimum requirements:
- CPU: x86_64-compatible processor
- RAM: 512 MB (minimum); 2 GB recommended for a smooth system with GUI
- Storage: 2 GB minimum for base installation (more required depending on desktop environment)
- Boot: UEFI or BIOS supported
- Network: Internet connection recommended for installation (packages downloaded online)

Description: Arch Linux is an independent Linux distribution, originally created by Judd Vinet. Installation is performed manually using only the terminal (command line).
It is recommended for users who want to build a fully customized system by themselves. Arch follows the KISS and DIY philosophies, which stand for Keep It Simple, Stupid and Do It Yourself, respectively.
It uses Pacman as its binary package manager. It does not have a default desktop environment, as installation is done from scratch via the terminal â€” the choice is up to the user.
